        <body>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Controlled Vocabularies in DH</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Originating from library and information science, controlled vocabularies provide essential terminology for organizing information, facilitating proper indexing and retrieval 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"0e4W6X31","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Harpring 2010)","plainCitation":"(Harpring 2010)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10497,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/4LWFP2SS"],"itemData":{"id":10497,"type":"book","call-number":"Z695.1.C85 H37 2010","edition":"1st ed","event-place":"Los Angeles, Calif","ISBN":"978-1-60606-018-6","language":"en","note":"OCLC: ocn456174098","number-of-pages":"245","publisher":"Getty Research Institute","publisher-place":"Los Angeles, Calif","source":"Library of Congress ISBN","title":"Introduction to controlled vocabularies: terminology for art, architecture, and other cultural works","title-short":"Introduction to controlled vocabularies","author":[{"family":"Harpring","given":"Patricia"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2010"]]},"citation-key":"harpring_introduction_2010"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Harpring 2010). In the DH context, researchers utilize controlled vocabularies to standardize annotations and machine-labeled entities. Particularly in Linked Open Data (LOD) projects, external authoritative vocabulary sources such as Getty AAT, Wikidata, and Iconclass, are linked to promote interoperability with other DH projects 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"NjVsarhz","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Zaytseva 2020)","plainCitation":"(Zaytseva 2020)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10509,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/CRDZNXNN"],"itemData":{"id":10509,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"Thesauri, taxonomies and other forms of controlled vocabularies represent a conceptual backbone of the research, playing an ever-increasing role in various aspects of the data management process. These resources are indispensable to determine common understanding allowing to systematically categorize and enrich research data in a consistent manner, as well as foster the data interoperability and integration among projects and web applications.","container-title":"DARIAH-Campus","language":"en","note":"publisher: DARIAH-Campus","source":"campus.dariah.eu","title":"Controlled Vocabularies and SKOS","URL":"https://campus.dariah.eu/en/resource/posts/controlled-vocabularies-and-skos","author":[{"family":"Zaytseva","given":"Ksenia"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,7]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2020",3,23]]},"citation-key":"zaytseva_controlled_2020"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Zaytseva 2020).
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The promise of interoperable vocabularies in computational and retrieval contexts is not without its critiques. Vocabularies, like any categorization, model our worldview and influence the research we produce. Within the field of library and information science, there have been criticisms of the positivity-neutrality in library stewardship, drawing on Foucault's concept of power/knowledge 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"VOBBDH1I","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Radford 1992; Martin 2021)","plainCitation":"(Radford 1992; Martin 2021)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10511,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/8DW6ER7H"],"itemData":{"id":10511,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"This article argues that modern conceptions of the library are informed by a particular view of knowledge grounded in early twentieth-century positivism. From this standpoint, the ideals of neutrality and access have achieved prevalence as the basis for understanding the institutionalized practices of modern libraries. This view of knowledge also serves to structure significantly the library experience of individual librarians and library users. The view of scientific knowledge developed in the works of Michel Foucault is described and from it the library experience is reconceptualized. From the Foucauldian perspective, the library is seen as a dynamic site for the possibility of new knowledge as well as a passive storehouse that provides access to individual facts. The library community is encouraged to consider such alternative views of knowledge as potential bases for viewing the modern library experience.","container-title":"The Library Quarterly: Information, Community, Policy","ISSN":"0024-2519","issue":"4","note":"publisher: University of Chicago Press","page":"408-424","source":"JSTOR","title":"Positivism, Foucault, and the Fantasia of the Library: Conceptions of Knowledge and the Modern Library Experience","title-short":"Positivism, Foucault, and the Fantasia of the Library","volume":"62","author":[{"family":"Radford","given":"Gary P."}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["1992"]]},"citation-key":"radford_positivism_1992"}},{"id":10520,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/NRURQV2B"],"itemData":{"id":10520,"type":"article-journal","container-title":"Cataloging & Classification Quarterly","DOI":"10.1080/01639374.2020.1871458","ISSN":"0163-9374, 1544-4554","issue":"2-3","journalAbbreviation":"Cataloging & Classification Quarterly","language":"en","page":"281-304","source":"DOI.org (Crossref)","title":"Records, Responsibility, and Power: An Overview of Cataloging Ethics","title-short":"Records, Responsibility, and Power","volume":"59","author":[{"family":"Martin","given":"Jennifer M."}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2021",4,3]]},"citation-key":"martin_records_2021"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Radford 1992; Martin 2021). In data-driven DH, Risam raises concerns about “cultural imperialism” of the Global North rooted in metadata schemas and controlled vocabularies in knowledge production within archives 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"NrvZLUIe","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Risam 2024)","plainCitation":"(Risam 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10512,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/Z73XCCEC"],"itemData":{"id":10512,"type":"chapter","abstract":"In the media-saturated twenty-first century, what can postcolonial studies tell us about contemporary data cultures? This chapter makes the case for a postcolonial approach to data. It begins by articulating where data fits within postcolonial studies of the present moment, shaped by changing geopolitics and emerging media. The chapter then proposes three interventions that postcolonial data studies could make: rethinking historical narratives of data, reinventing data practices, and reimagining data ethics. Collectively, the chapter argues, these tactics demonstrate how to excavate the past, present, and future of data and offer a path toward intervention in the inequitable politics of knowledge and data today.","container-title":"The Routledge Companion to Postcolonial and Decolonial Literature","ISBN":"978-1-00-319023-3","note":"number-of-pages: 11","publisher":"Routledge","title":"The Politics of Knowledge, the Politics of Data: Postcolonial Data Futures","title-short":"The Politics of Knowledge, the Politics of Data","author":[{"family":"Risam","given":"Roopika"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"risam_politics_2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Risam 2024). To combat the escalating issue of “data colonialism” 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"Ga4TiwMI","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Couldry / Mejias 2019)","plainCitation":"(Couldry / Mejias 2019)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10515,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/H9PD4HXP"],"itemData":{"id":10515,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"We are often told that data are the new oil. But unlike oil, data are not a substance found in nature. It must be appropriated. The capture and processing of social data unfolds through a process we call data relations, which ensures the “natural” conversion of daily life into a data stream. The result is nothing less than a new social order, based on continuous tracking, and offering unprecedented new opportunities for social discrimination and behavioral influence. We propose that this process is best understood through the history of colonialism. Thus, data relations enact a new form of data colonialism, normalizing the exploitation of human beings through data, just as historic colonialism appropriated territory and resources and ruled subjects for profit. Data colonialism paves the way for a new stage of capitalism whose outlines we only glimpse: the capitalization of life without limit.","container-title":"Television & New Media","DOI":"10.1177/1527476418796632","ISSN":"1527-4764, 1552-8316","issue":"4","journalAbbreviation":"Television & New Media","language":"en","page":"336-349","source":"DOI.org (Crossref)","title":"Data Colonialism: Rethinking Big Data’s Relation to the Contemporary Subject","title-short":"Data Colonialism","volume":"20","author":[{"family":"Couldry","given":"Nick"},{"family":"Mejias","given":"Ulises A."}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2019",5]]},"citation-key":"couldry_data_2019"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Couldry / Mejias 2019), the CARE principles were established to safeguard the data rights and interests of indigenous peoples 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"snD0itNY","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Carroll et al. 2020)","plainCitation":"(Carroll et al. 2020)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10460,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/SWEY5KR2"],"itemData":{"id":10460,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"The CODATA Data Science Journal is a peer-reviewed, open access, electronic journal, publishing papers on the management, dissemination, use and reuse of research data and databases across all research domains, including science, technology, the humanities and the arts. The scope of the journal includes descriptions of data systems, their implementations and their publication, applications, infrastructures, software, legal, reproducibility and transparency issues, the availability and usability of complex datasets, and with a particular focus on the principles, policies and practices for open data. All data is in scope, whether born digital or converted from other sources.","container-title":"Data Science Journal","DOI":"10.5334/dsj-2020-043","ISSN":"1683-1470","issue":"1","language":"en-US","source":"datascience.codata.org","title":"The CARE Principles for Indigenous Data Governance","URL":"https://datascience.codata.org/articles/10.5334/dsj-2020-043","volume":"19","author":[{"family":"Carroll","given":"Stephanie Russo"},{"family":"Garba","given":"Ibrahim"},{"family":"Figueroa-Rodríguez","given":"Oscar L."},{"family":"Holbrook","given":"Jarita"},{"family":"Lovett","given":"Raymond"},{"family":"Materechera","given":"Simeon"},{"family":"Parsons","given":"Mark"},{"family":"Raseroka","given":"Kay"},{"family":"Rodriguez-Lonebear","given":"Desi"},{"family":"Rowe","given":"Robyn"},{"family":"Sara","given":"Rodrigo"},{"family":"Walker","given":"Jennifer D."},{"family":"Anderson","given":"Jane"},{"family":"Hudson","given":"Maui"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",11,19]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2020",11,4]]},"citation-key":"carroll_care_2020"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Carroll et al. 2020).
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Numerous efforts have been undertaken by librarians and DH researchers to undo the power structures embedded within vocabularies and related pipelines, such as term changes 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"7B0lNQT2","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Bychowski et al. 2023)","plainCitation":"(Bychowski et al. 2023)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10524,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/EWM5GAP6"],"itemData":{"id":10524,"type":"article-journal","abstract":"This paper explores the Rare Book and Manuscript Section (RBMS) Controlled Vocabularies (RBMS CV) and their successor, the RBMS Controlled Vocabulary for Rare Materials Cataloging (RBMS CVRMC), both developed and maintained by the Rare Book and Manuscript Section of ALA/ACRL. These resources provide genre/form terms for use in special collections cataloging. Following a brief history of the development of the RBMS CV, this paper focuses on two projects: the creation of the integrated and linked data-compliant RBMS CVRMC and the revision and expansion of the thesaurus’ terms for prejudicial materials. We offer this as a case study of a community-created cataloging resource.","container-title":"Cataloging & Classification Quarterly","DOI":"10.1080/01639374.2023.2193950","ISSN":"0163-9374, 1544-4554","issue":"5-6","journalAbbreviation":"Cataloging & Classification Quarterly","language":"en","page":"626-645","source":"DOI.org (Crossref)","title":"Describing Special Collections: Two Projects to Modernize the RBMS Controlled Vocabularies","title-short":"Describing Special Collections","volume":"61","author":[{"family":"Bychowski","given":"Brenna"},{"family":"Hildebrand","given":"Ryan"},{"family":"Hoover","given":"Sarah"},{"family":"Reno","given":"Lauren"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2023",8,18]]},"citation-key":"bychowski_describing_2023"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Bychowski et al. 2023), inclusive data curation toolkits 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"7OZx3pVj","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Bourdages / Caporiccio 2020)","plainCitation":"(Bourdages / Caporiccio 2020)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10529,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/6CE97DDY"],"itemData":{"id":10529,"type":"book","language":"en-US","title":"The “Use Our Words” Toolkit","URL":"https://indigenouslis.ca/the-use-our-words-toolkit/","author":[{"family":"Bourdages","given":"Lauren"},{"family":"Caporiccio","given":"Kassandra"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,8]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2020"]]},"citation-key":"bourdages_use_2020"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Bourdages / Caporiccio 2020), software platforms 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"xXBhzpnz","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Rodriguez 2018)","plainCitation":"(Rodriguez 2018)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10533,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/XTWU8I2S"],"itemData":{"id":10533,"type":"article-journal","container-title":"Technical Services Quarterly","DOI":"10.1080/07317131.2018.1509454","ISSN":"0731-7131, 1555-3337","issue":"4","journalAbbreviation":"Technical Services Quarterly","language":"en","page":"406-407","source":"DOI.org (Crossref)","title":"Mukurtu Content Management System","volume":"35","author":[{"family":"Rodriguez","given":"Michael"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2018",10,2]]},"citation-key":"rodriguez_mukurtu_2018"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Rodriguez 2018), and participatory archiving projects 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"OwIDUXGP","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Humbel et al. 2024)","plainCitation":"(Humbel et al. 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10550,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/MCJZUPD6"],"itemData":{"id":10550,"type":"article-journal","container-title":"Journal of Documentation","note":"ISBN: 0022-0418\npublisher: Emerald Publishing Limited","title":"Socio-cultural challenges in collections digital infrastructures","author":[{"family":"Humbel","given":"Marco"},{"family":"Nyhan","given":"Julianne"},{"family":"Pearlman","given":"Nina"},{"family":"Vlachidis","given":"Andreas"},{"family":"Hill","given":"J. D."},{"family":"Flinn","given":"Andrew"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"humbel_socio-cultural_2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Humbel et al. 2024).
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>The Problem</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">One open issue remains regarding the annotation of cultural heritage in relation to historical stereotyping tropes. While we cannot eliminate these tropes without censoring the original works, we also cannot neutralize the concepts without losing historically situated knowledge. In this paper, we illustrate our approach to this issue by using a lightweight extension to existing vocabulary, through the example of the Digital Scholarly Edition of the Murten Panorama (Figure 1).</p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1001" width="15.769166666666667cm" height="1.728611111111111cm" url="/tmp/tmp25pjp04a/Pictures/34919a08d818d6165f488bea32f30b8a.png" rend="inline"/>
                    <head>Louis Braun, 
                        <hi rend="italic">The Panorama of the Battle of Murten</hi>, 1894, approximately 10 x 100 metres
                    </head>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">The Digital Scholarly Edition of the Murten Panorama is being developed as a collaborative semantic annotation project aimed at annotating entities (plots, objects, people, and locations) on the panorama and tracing their iconographical origins (Figure 2). This edition will serve as the main access point to the panorama and its scholarly interpretations, catering to a global audience 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"bdwJdcoK","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Jaquet / Kenderdine 2024)","plainCitation":"(Jaquet / Kenderdine 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10539,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/XCH87UUP"],"itemData":{"id":10539,"type":"chapter","container-title":"Panoramic and Immersive Media Studies Yearbook","ISBN":"978-3-11-133557-5","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0","note":"DOI: 10.1515/9783111335575-022","page":"295-306","publisher":"De Gruyter","source":"DOI.org (Crossref)","title":"The Digital Twin of the Panorama of the Battle of Murten: Notes on the Creation of the World’s Largest Image","title-short":"The Digital Twin of the Panorama of the Battle of Murten","URL":"https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783111335575-022/html","editor":[{"family":"Briggs","given":"Molly C."},{"family":"Logge","given":"Thorsten"},{"family":"Lowe","given":"Nicholas C."}],"author":[{"family":"Jaquet","given":"Daniel"},{"family":"Kenderdine","given":"Sarah"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,8]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024",11,4]]},"citation-key":"briggs_digital_2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Jaquet / Kenderdine 2024). Based on CIDOC-CRM 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"871Xn6hM","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Doerr 2009)","plainCitation":"(Doerr 2009)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":691,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/KCUULUPX"],"itemData":{"id":691,"type":"chapter","abstract":"SummaryIn the cultural heritage domain information systems are increasingly deployed, digital representations of physical objects are produced in immense numbers and there is a strong political pressure on memory institutions to make their holdings accessible to the public in digital form. The sector splits into a set of disciplines with highly specialized fields. Due to the resulting diversity, one can hardly speak about a “domain” in the sense of “domain ontologies” [33]. On the other side, study and research of the past is highly interdisciplinary. Characteristically, archaeology employs a series of “auxiliary” disciplines, such as archaeometry, archaeomedicine, archaeobotany, archaeometallurgy, archaeoastronomy, etc., but also historical sources and social theories.","collection-title":"International Handbooks on Information Systems","container-title":"Handbook on Ontologies","event-place":"Berlin, Heidelberg","ISBN":"978-3-540-92673-3","language":"en","note":"DOI: 10.1007/978-3-540-92673-3_21","page":"463-486","publisher":"Springer","publisher-place":"Berlin, Heidelberg","source":"Springer Link","title":"Ontologies for Cultural Heritage","URL":"https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-540-92673-3_21","author":[{"family":"Doerr","given":"Martin"}],"editor":[{"family":"Staab","given":"Steffen"},{"family":"Studer","given":"Rudi"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2020",8,9]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2009"]]},"citation-key":"doerrOntologiesCulturalHeritage2009"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Doerr 2009) and its extensions, the annotation data model aims to support historians' annotation tasks, including annotation with vocabulary, documenting provenance, constructing argumentative annotations, and incorporating a critical annotation module to complement standard vocabulary use 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"XH9HGSuD","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Chau et al. 2024)","plainCitation":"(Chau et al. 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10541,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/7CZBXQWI"],"itemData":{"id":10541,"type":"paper-conference","abstract":"Historically, the ability to reproduce visual works in print for comparison and detailed illustration has been crucial for art historical research and its dissemination. While this has always been possible, the study of big monolithic visual heritage can be greatly streamlined by an interactive digital research environment. The goal of our research is to develop an annotation platform that leverages linked open data to facilitate a thorough and scholarly description of big monolithic visual heritage. We will deploy our platform to craft a scholarly edition of the Murten Panorama (1894), offering high-quality, well-provenanced knowledge graph to both the public and scholars, giving them a window into the historical context of the creation of the 19th c. panoramic masterpiece.","container-title":"Proceedings of the fourth edition of the International Workshop on Semantic Web and Ontology Design for Cultural Heritage","event-place":"Tours, France","event-title":"SWODCH 2024","language":"en","publisher-place":"Tours, France","source":"Zotero","title":"Towards an Annotation Data Model for a Scholarly Semantic Annotation Platform in Visual Heritage:A Case Study Using the Murten Panorama","author":[{"family":"Chau","given":"Tsz Kin"},{"family":"Jaquet","given":"Daniel"},{"family":"Kenderdine","given":"Sarah"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024",10,30]]},"citation-key":"chau_towards_2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Chau et al. 2024).
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1002" width="16.002cm" height="9.024055555555556cm" url="/tmp/tmp25pjp04a/Pictures/34919a08d818d6165f488bea32f30b8a.png" rend="inline"/>
                    <head>Screenshot of the annotation project in development. Editors can compare visual sources and aggregate observations under common visual tropes</head>
                </figure>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">One notable challenge for the Digital Scholarly Edition concerns the presence of “Turkish Warrior” trope depicted in the panorama. “Turkish Warrior” functions as an allusion to “Enemy” that tracing its roots back to earlier representations of the Saracens and the Ottoman Turks 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"CDXBrZrB","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Caroff 2016)","plainCitation":"(Caroff 2016)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10517,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/8ATT77P8"],"itemData":{"id":10517,"type":"book","call-number":"741.647 0940902","event-place":"Paris","ISBN":"978-2-86377-254-6","language":"fre","publisher":"le Léopard d'or","publisher-place":"Paris","source":"BnF ISBN","title":"L'ost des Sarrasins: les musulmans dans l'iconographie médiévale France-Flandre, XIIIe-XVe siècle","title-short":"L'ost des Sarrasins","author":[{"family":"Caroff","given":"Fanny"}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["2016"]]},"citation-key":"caroff_ost_2016"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Caroff 2016). During the Burgundian Wars, the Swiss appropriated these allusions to call Charles the Bold the “Turk of the West” in their war propaganda 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"exd6UoSy","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Sieber-Lehmann 2011)","plainCitation":"(Sieber-Lehmann 2011)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10518,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/NECKL56W"],"itemData":{"id":10518,"type":"chapter","abstract":"Le terme, déjà utilisé à l'époque, désigne les hostilités qui opposèrent la Confédération des VIII cantons au duc de Bourgogne, Charles le Téméraire, de 1474 à 1477.","container-title":"Dictionnaire historique de la Suisse (DHS), version du 17.03.2011, traduit de l’allemand","language":"fr","title":"Bourgogne, guerres de","URL":"https://hls-dhs-dss.ch/articles/008881/2011-03-17/","author":[{"family":"Sieber-Lehmann","given":"Claudius"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,8]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2011",3,17]]},"citation-key":"sieber-lehmann_bourgogne_2011"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Sieber-Lehmann 2011). Finally, the fluid concept “Turkish Warrior” intersects with Edward Said's notion of Orientalism 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"XPXhaPHN","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Said 1979)","plainCitation":"(Said 1979)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10488,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/BRCZBIWH"],"itemData":{"id":10488,"type":"book","call-number":"DS12 .S24 1979","edition":"1st Vintage Books ed","event-place":"New York","ISBN":"978-0-394-74067-6","language":"en","number-of-pages":"368","publisher":"Vintage Books","publisher-place":"New York","source":"Library of Congress ISBN","title":"Orientalism","author":[{"family":"Said","given":"Edward W."}],"issued":{"date-parts":[["1979"]]},"citation-key":"said_orientalism_1979"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Said 1979), contributing to the exoticized representation seen in the panorama.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">In vocabulary-tagging annotation, the concepts to be associated with these representations include “Saracens (wd:Q105763)”, “Turks (iconclass:32B33(TURKS))”, “Enemy (iconclass:33B5)”, and “Orientalism (wd:Q42865)”. What is lacking here is the structure to present these concepts in a manner that is meaningful and accessible to a diverse audience, while avoiding the stigmatization that may result from linking certain populations to negative connotations.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Our Approach</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">While the ultimate fix should be establishing a neutral term that reflects the semiotics of such visual tropes, this is not always feasible, as certain knowledge may exceed the editor's expertise and the scope of the task. Consequently, we propose historicization as a lightweight solution to address this issue. Instead of sanitizing the vocabulary to terms like “imaginary oriental enemy”, we aim to fully reveal the context in which these representations were created. We adopt the notion of institutional fact from CRMaaa, an ongoing extension of the CIDOC-CRM that aims to represent the historically bound collective beliefs for scholarly argumentation, grounded in the idea of speech acts in the Austinian and Searlean sense 
                    <?biblio ADDIN ZOTERO_ITEM CSL_CITATION {"citationID":"io2Di9Hp","properties":{"formattedCitation":"(Swiss Art Research Infrastructure / Takin.solutions 2024)","plainCitation":"(Swiss Art Research Infrastructure / Takin.solutions 2024)","noteIndex":0},"citationItems":[{"id":10542,"uris":["http://zotero.org/users/416509/items/ECGJDYLS"],"itemData":{"id":10542,"type":"software","title":"CRM Art and Architectural Argumentation ontology","URL":"https://ontome.net/project/69","version":"1.6","author":[{"literal":"Swiss Art Research Infrastructure"},{"literal":"Takin.solutions"}],"accessed":{"date-parts":[["2024",12,8]]},"issued":{"date-parts":[["2024"]]},"citation-key":"swiss_art_research_infrastructure_crm_2024"}}],"schema":"https://github.com/citation-style-language/schema/raw/master/csl-citation.json"}?>(Swiss Art Research Infrastructure / Takin.solutions 2024).
                </p>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">Figure 3 illustrates the knowledge graph we developed using CRMaaa to document the historical context of the concept “Turkish Warrior”. At the bottom, a point of interest (POI) from the panorama featuring a Turkish warrior is observed and assigned the term “Turkish Warrior (visual trope)” from a local vocabulary. This vocabulary is linked to an external vocabulary through a 
                    <hi rend="italic">skos:mappingRelation</hi>, resembling the typical usage patterns of external vocabularies in DH projects. What extends this pattern is the connection to 
                    <hi rend="italic">ZE12 Referential Status</hi> which provides three properties: 1) 
                    <hi rend="italic">ZP36 ascribes referent</hi> to capture the connotation of the term, 2) 
                    <hi rend="italic">ZP75 applies for context</hi> to specify the socio-cultural context and 3) 
                    <hi rend="italic">ZP4 holds for</hi> to document the collective this discourse is applicable. Following 
                    <hi rend="italic">ZP113 has successor status</hi>, we also document how the terminology is appropriated from its preceding status. Regarding provenance, researchers can leverage the 
                    <hi rend="italic">E13 Attribute Assignment</hi> to record citations for a vocabulary-context association.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1003" width="16.002cm" height="17.314333333333334cm" url="/tmp/tmp25pjp04a/Pictures/34919a08d818d6165f488bea32f30b8a.png" rend="inline"/>
                    <head>Knowledge graph to represent the historical signification and context of “Turkish Warrior” in relation to the Murten Panorama</head>
                </figure>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Applications</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">We plan to use the proposed structure for the information page shown in Figure 4 in our Digital Scholarly Edition, providing readers with a deeper understanding of the historical context of the term. Additionally, through SPARQL federated queries, this structure can serve as an autonomous, lightweight extension to existing vocabulary systems, offering a 
                    <hi rend="italic">context-indexed</hi> facet. In terms of potential applications, a cross-cultural collaborative knowledge base can be established to aggregate the evolving contexts of vocabularies using NLP or LLM-based extraction<ref n="1" target="ftn1"/>. Ultimately, this system has the potential to provide analytic value, for instance, in answering questions such as who has been ascribed “The Enemy” by a given collective over time.
                </p>
                <figure>
                    <graphic n="1004" width="15.404041666666666cm" height="25.200680555555557cm" url="/tmp/tmp25pjp04a/Pictures/34919a08d818d6165f488bea32f30b8a.png" rend="inline"/>
                    <head>Information page to represent the historical signification and context of “Turkish Warrior”</head>
                </figure>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
                <head>Conclusion</head>
                <p style="text-align: left; ">In conclusion, this paper highlights the necessity and motivation behind historicizing the power/knowledge embedded in vocabulary systems. By utilizing CRMaaa, we demonstrate a lightweight “quick fix” approach. Future work could focus on adapting the current CRM model into an SKOS extension to achieve greater impact by aligning with the popular SKOS-based vocabulary systems.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="div1" rend="DH-Heading1">
